<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / After The VAT Vote: Wealth of tax options to make up Budget
shortfall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY and PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chancellor has probably received as much advice as to the contents of
his so-called mini-budget to be delivered today as for the main event
delivered to the House of Commons only nine days ago.
Newspapers, economic analysts, and even his political opponents have all
offered their chosen tax options - but Mr Clarke has a well-earned
reputation for being able to produce political surprises.
His announced intention is to plug the gap left in the Budget by the
decision to drop the proposed increase on value added tax on fuel. The size
of this gap is the first area of dispute, for while the gross cost of the
measure was Pounds 1.5bn, that included measures to offset its impact on the
elderly.
Mr Chris Giles, a researcher at the Institute of Fiscal Studies, said
yesterday that withdrawal of all or part of the planned safety net for those
hit by the increase in VAT would result in 'clawback' of between Pounds 100m
and Pounds 400m.
'In fact he doesn't have to do anything at all,' said Mr Giles. 'This is a
drop in the ocean compared with the forecast for the PSBR for 1995-96 of
Pounds 21.5bn. The forecast error on the PSBR is around Pounds 6bn wrong
every year.'
The chancellor may be enticed by the idea of putting together a package of
smaller measures. That way he will avoid hitting one group of taxpayers.
One option fast becoming a favourite yesterday was putting a penny on a
litre of all road fuels: leaded, non-leaded, and diesel. This would bring in
Pounds 500m and serve to replace one measure portrayed as environmentally
friendly - increasing VAT on fuel - with another 'green' tax. A rise of 2p
would achieve the chancellor's aims in one move.
Mr Roger Bootle, chief economist at Midland Global Markets, favours the
petrol option as it would add only 0.2 per cent to the Retail Price Index
compared with the 0.4 per cent which would have resulted from the rise in
VAT on fuel.
Until yesterday morning, when the chancellor decided to put up interest
rates by a half point, another favoured option was a reduction in mortgage
interest relief to 10 per cent. This would bring in the required Pounds 1bn
revenue but would be politically troublesome after an interest rate rise.
'He has a whole variety of options,' said Mr Neil McKinnon, chief economist
at Citibank. 'Clearly the revenue-raising option is more politically
contentious . . . but he may decide to raise revenue through the back door.'
One suggestion was cutting the married couple's allowance by 10 per cent -
another measure which could bring in Pounds 1bn.
Most analysts ruled out an increase in direct taxation as too politically
risky for a government which has staked so much on the long-term reduction
of income tax.
A 0.5p rise in the basic rate of income tax, however, would bring in the
required Pounds 1bn as would a  1/2 percentage point rise in VAT.
Mr McKinnon judged that the VAT option 'would be adding fuel to the fire'
after Tuesday night's defeat at the hands of opposition parties and rebel
Conservative MPs. 'I think what he might do is either lift a freeze on
(some) excise duties or dip into the contingency reserve.'
However, Mr Adam Cole, economist at James Capel, was one of several analysts
who believed that it was important for the chancellor to strike a tough
fiscal stance in the mini-budget and that raiding the contingency reserve -
the government's emergency fund - would displease the markets.
</TEXT>
