<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / After The VAT Vote: Rightwingers want whip move reversed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rightwing Conservative MPs yesterday demanded the restoration of the party
whip to nine Tory Euro-rebels to contain the political damage after
Tuesday's defeat over value added tax on fuel.
As cabinet ministers and backbenchers assessed the political implications of
scrapping the second VAT increase a group of Tory MPs blamed the
government's defeat on the recent expulsion of rebels who voted against the
European finance bill.
The rightwingers noted that eight of the nine MPs - including Mrs Teresa
Gorman, Mr Richard Shepherd and Mr Nicholas Winterton - had failed to
support the government on Tuesday. And they expressed fears that the group
could rebel again.
One MP said: 'I would like a clear sign that these people will be reinstated
at the start of next year at the earliest.' He said the government would
suffer if a group of populist MPs was allowed to fester as 'a party within a
party'.
Another complained that the expulsions demonstrated that a cabinet
'dominated by centre-left politicians' was keen to mete out punishment to
MPs on the right.
He said: 'We have recently seen people like Hugh Dykes manoeuvring to bring
down the Post Office bill, which would have been one of the key items of
legislation this year. But they have suffered nothing.'
There was far less agreement in the party over the other main key issue now
facing Mr John Major's government: how to plug the Pounds 1bn fiscal gap
created by the climbdown on raising VAT to 17 1/2 per cent.
Rightwing MPs called for Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, to announce more
spending cuts in his 'mini-budget' today.
But others hoped the chancellor would raise more revenue - possibly on wine
or tobacco - amid signs that little more could be squeezed from a spending
round that has already been tough.
An MP who closely monitors economic strategy said: 'He has to replace a tax
measure with a tax measure.' The chancellor would want to avoid altering the
structure of fiscal planning in the Red Book.
There were signs, though, that Mr Clarke might risk a new rebellion on tax
if he were to introduce a half-percentage point increase in the general rate
of VAT to 18 per cent.
One mainstream MP said: 'He cannot guarantee getting the whole-hearted
support of colleagues.' He said that the party had to move away from its
tax-raising image.
Another said the chancellor would need to resist taking his revenge on the
party by introducing punitive taxation. 'He needs to avoid the temptation of
saying 'I told you so' to the rebels,' the MP said.
Above all, there was debate about the extent to which Tuesday night's vote
had damaged the political future for Mr Major and Mr Clarke.
Mr Major's prime ministership was widely seen as safe because the closing
date for applications to the party's annual leadership contest closed last
week. 'He is very lucky the VAT issue did not come up earlier than it did,'
said one MP, claiming that this week's controversy would have been forgotten
in 12 months.
But some privately admitted that Mr Clarke's determination to take on the
rebels and go through with the VAT increase in his Budget had damaged his
chances of becoming leader.
One MP said that Mr Clarke had had a faultless spell as chancellor, but that
he had resisted repeated calls for VAT to be scrapped. 'It will be difficult
for him to get over that mistake,' he said.
Mr Jonathan Aitken, the chief secretary to the Treasury, was one of a number
of cabinet ministers who expressed confidence that the party could restore
its fortunes in the new year.
But there were private concerns, too, that the government was so weak that
it could soon face a new crisis.
</TEXT>
