<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / After The VAT Vote: Major ebullient despite reverse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAMBERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For a prime minister who only a few hours earlier had lost such an important
vote in the Commons, Mr John Major was on remarkably ebullient form.
Fulfilling a longstanding engagement to breakfast yesterday with a group of
businessmen at a London hotel he looked tired but spoke from notes with
passion and some humour.
Mr Major talked optimistically about the recovery, defended his decision to
suspend from the Tory party eight Eurosceptic MPs who had voted against the
government on a confidence motion, and called for a more rational debate on
Europe.
He said the previous night's rejection by MPs of the second stage of value
added tax on domestic fuel had been a mistake. He did not know of any tax
measure that had been so misrepresented.
The great beneficiaries of the vote to hold valued added tax on domestic
fuel at 8 per cent would not be the old and the sick, but the reasonably
well-off middle class - people in the room.
The chancellor would be taking the necessary steps to repair the financial
damage. 'There should be no shred of doubt about this - we are going to take
no risks with the economy.' Time and again since the 1950s the economy had
been driven off course by inflation and he was 'sick and tired' of it.
This time it would be different. 'That is the bedrock on which our economic
policy is built, a bedrock of low inflation. I hope no one doubts the
determination of this government to pursue an anti-inflation strategy.'
Recent growth rates were unsustainable but there was an unprecedented
opportunity for sustained long-term growth. He said: 'We will take no risks
with the recovery.' He was determined to pursue policies that would lead to
lower unemployment and less regulation.
Mr Major said British industry - British Steel and the motor manufacturers
were examples - had been transformed in recent years. 'Is this just a normal
cyclical recovery? I don't think so.' Everyone had told him that by now
there would be a balance of payments crisis, an inflationary spiral, wage
inflation. None of this had come about.
He then moved on to Europe, remarking how frustrated he was that the
argument was only being heard from the extreme positions on either side.
Britain's interests lay in the heart of Europe, and it was about time that
industry stood up and supported that view.
</TEXT>
