<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / After The VAT Vote: City gloomy on fallout from political
turmoil
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, CONNER MIDDELMANN and GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The City reacted positively to yesterday's base rate rise, with most
analysts agreeing that there were good reasons for the increase on economic,
rather than political, grounds.
Yet many traders took a gloomy view of the turmoil engulfing the government,
fearing that continued political uncertainty could command a higher risk
premium on UK assets.
Most economists had been predicting an imminent rate increase, but they were
divided on whether it would occur in December or January.
Mr Bill Martin, chief economist at UBS, said: 'The chancellor's decision to
raise base rates immediately following the government's Commons defeat is
wholly justified by economic conditions.'
Mr Adam Cole, UK economist at James Capel, said: 'The economic case for a
rise in rates is compelling. The economy is growing at well above its
sustainable rate, and inflationary pressures are increasing.'
Mr John Shepperd, chief economist at Yamaichi International (Europe), said:
'I don't think anyone can quibble with the basic view that a base rate rise
was justified.'
But Mr Roger Bootle, chief economist at Midland Global Markets, said that,
in the approach to Christmas, 'the impact on consumer confidence of a base
rate rise may be quite severe. If you really do think the retail sector is
weak, this could deal it a pretty serious blow'.
While the base rate news was welcome, and helped the pound and gilts to
rally, the government's Commons defeat over value added tax had a more
sobering effect.
A City professional said: 'The headlines this will generate internationally
will emphasise the degree of political risk surrounding UK assets and
probably deter some overseas investors from investing in them. In recent
months the markets have become highly sensitised to political risk - for
instance in countries like Italy, Sweden or France - and in terms of risk
candidates, the last 24 hours have pushed the UK up the league table.'
One dealer said he had received a string of phone calls in recent weeks from
US investors worried about the political outlook in the UK. He said: 'They
see politics as a real risk.'
Another said that in coming months UK financial markets would be caught
between two opposing forces, Britain's healthy economic fundamentals and the
fragile political situation.
He said: 'Politics will be a negative influence on the markets for the
remainder of this government's life. In the battle between politics and
economics, the latter will probably win - but the pendulum will swing back
and forth between the two, leaving the markets vulnerable.'
Another dealer said: 'The markets are quite content with how the government
is managing the economy in the short term. Of more concern is the longer
term and how long the government can go on like this, stumbling from one
crisis to another.'
He added: 'The erosion of power that has been seen over the last few months
may mean that the government will become so weak that it will begin to make
concessions to different interest groups. This may mean greater spending and
wage inflation.'
A pessimistic UK equity dealer said: 'I don't think this government will
even make it to April 1997. As it is, the Conservatives have a very small
majority, and if they lose another few by-elections that majority could get
squeezed further.'
But, he said, after 15 years of Tory rule, most market participants could
not overcome the psychological barrier of contemplating a Labour government.
He added: 'The majority of the market still believes the Conservatives can't
lose the next election, but I think there's a good chance they might.'
</TEXT>
