<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / After The VAT Vote: Kenneth Clarke's comments on interest
rates rise
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, commenting on the rise in interest rates,
said:
'After my monthly discussion with the governor (of the Bank of England), I
have decided to increase interest rates by half per cent, in order to
sustain economic recovery with low inflation. This decision is in line with
my clear policy of taking no risks with inflation. The governor decided to
implement the change immediately because there were no reasons for delay and
he wanted to avoid market uncertainties.
'Underlying inflation is currently 2.0 per cent, the lowest level for 27
years and well below the European average. We need to ensure that inflation
remains low, so that the recovery is sustained, and leads to higher living
standards and secure jobs. The only way to make sure inflation stays low is
to act in good time.
'I raised interest rates by half per cent in September in order to take no
risks with inflation. This further rise today is the right response to
continuing indications in the last few months of inflationary pressures as
growth has strengthened. I intend to deliver the plans I announced in the
Budget to return the PSBR to balance and to make the economy perform better.
Together with these plans, this move in interest rates will help to underpin
a healthy and sustained recovery.'
</TEXT>
