<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / Oftel reopens the rule book: Alan Cane says the watchdog
sees a different role for itself allied with fresh regulations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK has the most liberalised telecommunications market in the world.
It also has one of the most complex, with emerging competition encouraged by
a raft of regulation designed to give newcomers room to grow in the shadow
of British Telecommunications.
Yesterday's consultative paper from Oftel, the telecoms regulator, solicits
opinions on questions at the heart of the worldwide debate on how best to
manage the evolution of telecoms from state-owned monopoly to fully
competitive free market.
Few would oppose the need for a measure of regulation after liberalisation.
Mr Don Cruickshank, Oftel director-general, said yesterday that Britain's
tangle of regulation was no accident.
He said: 'This burst of regulatory effort is inevitable as the emergence of
competition generates new problems and argument for regulators to adjudicate
on.
'If we are to ensure that competition does not wither on the vine,
abandonment of monopolies and reserved rights must be coupled with the
adoption of rules.'
The question addressed by the paper is what kind of rules apply in a market
such as the UK, where competition is still only emerging.
The message from Oftel is that it would like to see itself policing the
market for anti-competitive behaviour rather than continuing in its role as
a calculator of regulated prices. Mr Cruickshank pointed out, however, that
a move towards comprehensive coverage of potential anti-competitive
behaviour would work only if the right enforcement mechanisms were in place.
Sir Iain Vallance, BT chairman, said this week that he wanted freedom from
retail price controls from 1997, when the existing regime will be reviewed,
and an end to preferential support for market newcomers.
The Oftel paper suggests that newcomers have to be protected against BT
through a modification of the access deficit contribution regime. It does,
however, raise the possibility that ADC might vanish.
Oftel speculates that if the line rental cap were lifted, BT would not raise
line rental charges significantly, assuming the existing overall cap on
prices remained in force.
It says: 'With the overall price cap set at RPI minus 7.5 per cent, the
bills of most customers would fall even if BT rebalanced (its line rental
and call charges) quite quickly.'
The paper also questions the high cost to BT of the universal service
obligation, designed to ensure that the isolated and the infirm have
economical access to a basic phone service.
Research published yesterday by Analysys, a European telecoms consultancy,
supports the Oftel conclusions. It says the net cost to BT of its obligation
is between Pounds 50m and Pounds 120m, somewhat less than estimates by
experts which have been as high as Pounds 400m.
</TEXT>
<XX>
