<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / What is the access deficit contribution?
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BT's prices are capped by a series of formulae which relate its tariffs to
the retail prices index. It receives fees, which are closely monitored by
the regulator, from competitors for accepting and delivering calls in its
role as dominant operator with a network which stretches almost everywhere
in the UK.
As network owner BT is obliged to provide a universal service at reasonable
cost. In practice, it is prevented by Oftel from charging line rental which
would reflect the fully allocated costs of providing and maintaining
customer connections to the network. BT funds this access deficit through
artificially high call charges. When a competitor connects to BT's network
to route a call to its destination, the cost of carriage charge includes the
cost of providing customers' connections. The access deficit contribution is
intended to compensate BT for this loss of revenue.
Most of its competitors have had part of this fee waived as an encouragement
to competition. Interconnection charges to BT can represent between a half
and two-thirds of a competing operator's costs.
</TEXT>
