<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / BT may gain right to raise line rental fees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Telecommunications could be allowed to raise line rental charges
under one of the controversial options set out in a consultative paper
published yesterday by Oftel, the telecoms regulator.
If BT took full advantage of its potential new freedom home line rentals
might rise by more than Pounds 50 a year - although Oftel says competition
and consumer resistance make it unlikely that BT would raise rental charges
significantly.
The paper is expected to initiate the most far-reaching debate about
telecoms regulation since BT was privatised and Mercury Communications
formed as a direct competitor in 1984.
The consultative document discusses a range of regulatory issues but comes
to few conclusions. A definitive statement is expected next summer after a
consultation period running to the end of March.
The issues discussed include changes in ways of calculating the
interconnection charge paid to BT by its competitors for picking up or
delivering calls made through their networks. The interconnection regime has
been a point of contention with companies such as Mercury, which say it is
unfair and arbitrary.
One proposal is that the access deficit contribution (ADC), a charge to
competitors to recompense BT for its obligation to maintain a comprehensive
network, should be abolished. Currently only Mercury pays ADCs.
Interconnection charges represent a significant proportion of a telecom
operator's costs. Mr Don Cruickshank, Oftel director-general, makes it clear
that he finds the present ADC situation unsatisfactory and will insist on
changes.
He says BT's present cap on price rises - the retail prices index minus 7
1/2 per cent - will be maintained until 1997, when it is due for review. He
says BT will continue to be required to offer the same prices to customers
throughout the UK.
His underlying message is that it may be time to move to a more openly
competitive environment where BT has greater pricing freedoms and Oftel's
chief task is policing anti-competitive behaviour, backed by tougher
competition laws.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
