<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / Business steps up move from central London
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The number of office occupiers moving out of central London has risen
sharply this year and is likely to remain high as companies rationalise
premises, says an annual survey by the surveyors Jones Lang Wootton.
Central London - the City and the West End - has lost about 200,000 office
jobs over 30 years as a direct result of companies decentralising operations
away from the capital. Decentralisation fell in 1992 and 1993 as the cost of
central London office accommodation fell in relation to other regions during
recession.
Nineteen big organisations moved a total of 8,440 jobs out of central London
this year, up from 3,500 last year. While only 11 organisations have firm
plans to move next year and in 1996, the level of prospective moves,
involving 55 organisations, is at a historically high level.
The new wave of relocation away from central London appears to be driven by
wider corporate rationalisation rather than outright concern for occupancy
costs.
More than half of the companies likely to move out of central London were
motivated by the desire to consolidate their number of sites as part of
wider restructuring. As a result, 40 per cent of companies questioned
planned to move to locations where they had existing premises.
Only 37 per cent cited occupancy costs as the main reason for their move. In
the 1980s this percentage was typically more than 50 per cent.
The narrower cost differential between the south-east of England and other
regions means that companies moving out of central London are more likely to
move only short distances.
Favoured destinations for decentralisation are those within the immediate
orbit of central London, such as Hammersmith and Docklands, which offer
proximity to the capital and significant cost savings over the West End or
City.
</TEXT>
