<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / Councils rapped on shake-up plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Councils are not preparing properly for reorganisation, the Audit Commission
says in a report published today.
It says some councils are failing to talk to their neighbours, planning
prematurely to take over other councils' services, or making financial
commitments which incoming councils would inherit.
Under reorganisation, due to take place in 1996, all-purpose unitary
authorities will replace the existing two-tier structure in Wales and in
several areas of England.
The greatest fear is that councils facing abolition will spend
irresponsibly. At the last reorganisation, in 1974, the number of new
swimming pools tripled.
Mr Bob Chilton, the commission's head of local government studies, said the
chances of another 'swimming pool binge' had been reduced. Several councils
with extensive reserves were, however, planning big capital projects, while
at least one was planning to set a nil council tax in its final year to
highlight the costs of reorganisation. This would burden new authorities
with unnecessary costs.
The commission says councils are refusing to improve their records for use
by incoming authorities, or to prepare for competitive tendering of
white-collar services, which will be compulsory.
Paving the Way: Helping Councils Prepare for the Future. Audit Commission.
HMSO. Pounds 7.50.
</TEXT>
