<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / Cross-party MPs urge code of workers' rights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER, Employment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government should publish a new code of workers' rights which should be
included in employment contracts, a cross-party committee of MPs said
yesterday.
In a report on the future of trade unions the Commons employment committee
split on party lines. But Labour and Tory members agreed that workers did
not fully understand their rights and obligations.
The committee said the government should reduce uncertainty by introducing a
code of individual rights of workers and incorporating it into employment
contracts.
The report said: 'In simplifying the web of rights it would also be possible
to extend rights of consultation from recognised trade unions to individual
workers on a collective basis where these workers are not unionised.'
The Conservative-dominated committee said unions faced a 'serious challenge'
after a sharp fall in membership, and called on them to make more effort to
attract members from the private sector or face becoming public sector-only
bodies.
The report said unions faced a challenge over how much they could still
exercise their traditional core function of collective bargaining, but the
committee was 'pleased to note the efforts of the Trades Union Congress and
some of its member unions to reassess and extend the services which they
provide and so retain and increase their membership. There is a clear need
for trade unions to launch more recruitment campaigns explaining the
benefits on offer in a modern context.'
The committee urged the government to consult the TUC about matters 'within
its province', and said unions should be asked to help shape the new modern
apprenticeship schemes.
Four Labour MPs who refused to sign the final document, said of the majority
report: 'There is in fact much we can agree with, and we welcome the
recognition that trade unions have an important role to play. This shows a
distinct change from some years ago.'
Mr John Monks, general secretary of the TUC, said: 'Today's report is a
welcome break from the anti-union prejudices of the 1980s.'
The committee spilt over whether employees should have a legal right to
representation by a union, as they do elsewhere in Europe. Labour MPs said
this was essential, but Tories said such matters should be left to voluntary
agreement between management and employees.
Another split was over Europe. The committee acknowledged that the future of
Britain's unions might be strongly linked to developments in European public
and social policy. However, the report merely said: 'The UK's attitude to
such legislation will be crucial.'
The Labour document said: 'We believe it is only a matter of time before
Britain reverses its opt-out of European social policy. It is therefore
inevitable that the pattern of British industrial relations - including its
legal framework - will move increasingly towards a common European model.'
</TEXT>
