<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / Stock Exchange steps up insider dealing rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Stock Exchange is pressing ahead with proposals to halt trading in
individual companies' shares if there is evidence that price-sensitive
information has leaked.
According to senior Stock Exchange officials the new rules may be tougher
than originally planned, and are likely to involve the immediate suspension
of trading in a company's shares following anomalous transactions in those
shares, rather than a phased path to a trading halt as originally planned.
Following a two month consultation period the proposals - the aim of which
is to minimise the effects of insider trading on investors' confidence in
the market - are expected to be turned into formal policies in the coming
few weeks.
Under the original proposal, the process of halting trading in a company's
shares would have been staggered in two phases. The first phase, known as
making a security 'indicative', would have involved a temporary removal of
the obligation on market makers to deal at prices quoted on the Seaq
electronic trading screens.
When the shares had been given this indicative status the exchange would
have contacted the relevant company and asked it to put out a statement - if
it was in takeover talks or was in possession of other forms of undisclosed
price sensitive information.
Pending the publication of such a statement the exchange would have called a
complete halt to trading in the shares.
Participants in the stock market have told the exchange that they are
concerned that the volatility of trading would be increased sharply during
the period when the shares were indicative, leading to a heightened risk
that unwary investors would deal at a price that they would later deem to be
too high or too low, depending on the contents of any corporate
announcement.
As a result the exchange is likely to call a halt to trading in a company's
shares the moment that the Integrated Monitoring and Surveillance System
(IMAS) detects an unusually strong surge in trading volumes, or movement in
the share price, without making the shares indicative first.
On Tuesday, however, the exchange ran a partial pilot test of the original
proposals. It made shares in the banknote paper-maker Portals indicative at
12.41pm, 50 minutes after IMAS detected a strong surge in dealing volumes.
At 12.10pm, the exchange asked Portals' stockbroker, Warburg Securities,
whether the company was involved in any transaction which could explain the
share surge. If so, it wanted Portals to put out a statement.
At just after 1.00pm Portals put out a statement that it was in talks with
De La Rue, the banknote printer, about increasing commercial links between
the two companies.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Safety &amp; Standards.
    TECH  Services &amp; Services use.
</TP>
