<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / Political Notebook: Europe - the Tories' fatal attraction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is Europe that really counts. Amid the stunned confusions of ministers
and Conservative MPs at Westminster it was possible to find a theory for
each and for all seasons. Most had the government stumbling to defeat at the
next general election. Some included a coup d'etat to replace Mr John Major
with Mr Michael Heseltine or, just maybe, Mr Kenneth Clarke. Others gave the
prime minister another year before his party disintegrated into two or three
warring factions. There was even the odd senior Tory willing to venture that
in the grand sweep of history this was no more than a ripple: the government
might yet recover.
Certainly Mr Major seems to think so. In the early hours of yesterday
morning he stormed from the government whips' office after what observers
took to be a less-than-cheerful inquest into the VAT defeat with Mr Clarke.
Hours later he was addressing a dawn breakfast for captains of industry with
the exuberant demeanour of the victor rather than the vanquished. No one
knows whether he will decide before the election that there are better
things to do in life than be pelted with bricks by members of his own party.
No one can doubt that he is tough.
But, once the speculation and the scheming at Westminster is stripped away,
Europe emerges again and again as the Tories' fatal attraction. Mr Major
made the point himself when he urged his business audience not to let the
extremists - the sceptics or the federalists - dominate the argument.
Britain could remain at the heart of Europe without selling its sovereign
soul.
Tell that to the exiled sceptics on the backbenches whose well-planned
ambush ensured the VAT defeat; or to the small band of Euro-enthusiasts who
mutter these days that Mr Major has been captured by the sceptics. If there
is to be a rational debate about Britain's future in Europe then the
government and the Tory party must demonstrate first that they are capable
of conducting it.
The sceptics hold sway - not just the irreconcilable fanatics but a broader
swathe of rightish Tories whose instincts if not their intellects have
driven them to seek political security in anti-Europeanism. The
pro-Europeans talk about a passing phase but the centre of gravity in the
party has shifted. Mr Peter Lilley can now state confidently that the
government will fight the next election on a Euro-sceptic platform.
The cabinet's Euro enthusiasts have let the argument go by default. Sure, Mr
Clarke will tell anyone who asks him that he still favours a single European
currency. He has been active behind-the-scenes in trying to prevent Mr Major
promising a referendum on monetary union. But there has been no concerted
effort to persuade the doubters that Europe is about more than preventing
the bureaucrats of Brussels from interfering in the lives of Britons.
So when Mr Major and his cabinet colleagues travel to the Essen EU summit
later today their posture will be defensive. Let's hope, one minister
remarked this week, that Chancellor Helmut Kohl does not say anything silly
about a federal Europe and hand fresh ammunition to the sceptics.
Mr Douglas Hurd is preparing a strategy to tilt back the balance - to remind
Conservatives that they have prospered as the party of Europe. His ideas for
a sharper European defence identity have been delayed but not shelved by the
tensions in the Western alliance caused by Bosnia.
He is working up proposals for changes in the shape of the Brussels
Commission and in the role of national parliaments to provide a positive
British agenda for the 1996 intergovernmental conference.
More mundanely, Mr Hurd has sent to every minister a long-overdue balance
sheet putting the advantages alongside the inconveniences of EU membership.
The idea is that they might find time to have the occasional good word to
say about Britain's membership. Tory party activists can expect something
similar in their Christmas mail.
But the opportunity may already have passed to re-establish a common
platform on which the bulk of the Conservative party can stand. Certainly
some of the sceptics will be impossible to win back for any programme other
than progressive disengagement.
It is no good Mr Hurd producing carefully crafted arguments for Britain's
place in Europe if cabinet colleagues are permitted to flirt with the
possibility of eventual withdrawal. Mr Major cannot complain about the
divisions in his party unless he can demonstrate that he leads a united
cabinet. Last night he signalled that he realises time is running out and
opened the door still wider to the possibility of a referendum.
It may be too late. But if that is so, Europe has the capacity to break more
than this prime minister and this government. It might well break
permanently the Conservative party.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9199 General Government, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
