<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / EU finance bill completes final Commons' hurdle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The bill that triggered the political storm engulfing Mr John Major's
government last night completed its Commons stages with a convincing
majority.
The European Union finance bill, increasing Britain's payments to the EU
budget, received its third reading early this morning - a day earlier than
originally planned.
With Labour abstaining, only 23 MPs voted against it, allowing the measure
to pass by an overwhelming majority of 272. No Conservatives voted against
but several did not vote.
This is likely to clear more time in the parliamentary timetable for
debating today's mini-Budget, caused by the enforced scrapping of the second
stage of value added tax on domestic fuel.
The bill's second reading last week led to the withdrawal of the
Conservative whip from eight Tory Eurosceptics after they ignored Mr Major's
decision to make the matter an issue of confidence and abstained.
The bill now passes to the Lords, but peers will be unable to amend it
because it is a finance measure.
Meanwhile, it emerged during earlier exchanges that Mr Major had moved
closer to an understanding with Eurosceptics by backing stronger measures to
prevent EU money being used for fraud in Britain.
Mr Bill Cash, MP for Stafford, revealed Mr Major's role in meeting
Eurosceptic demands to combat fraudsters.
Mr Major agreed that the Commons public accounts committee should be asked
to examine the accounts of non-government agencies which have received EU
funds.
Mr David Heathcoat-Amory, paymaster-general, stressed that ministers could
not direct the committee - but confirmed that Mr Major wanted EU fraud to be
a priority.
</TEXT>
