<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / Post-VAT vote of confidence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government, still reeling from its defeat over value added tax on
domestic fuel, survived a confidence vote in the Commons yesterday.
A key provision in the European Union finance bill was approved almost
without challenge.
Mr David Heathcoat-Amory, the paymaster general, confirmed it was a
confidence issue, but there was none of the drama which marked the second
reading of the bill, when eight Tory backbenchers were deprived of the
Conservative whip for failing to back the government, reducing it to a
minority adminis-tration.
Mr Dennis Skinner, the leftwing Labour MP for Bolsover, failed to make Tory
backbenchers troop through the government lobby over a vote on the EU's 'own
resources'.
His unusually muted opposition was not heard by Mr Michael Morris, chairman
of the committee, who ruled that the clause had been approved without a
division.
A 52-minute speech by Mr Bill Cash, Tory MP for Stafford and a leading
Eurosceptic, indicated that the committee stage of the bill was unlikely to
be swift.
</TEXT>
