<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / Republicans agree to procedural changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Republican members of the House of Representatives agreed yesterday to plans
for a change in the House's procedural rules that would make it much more
difficult to raise taxes, George Graham writes.
The members agreed to require a three-fifths majority for any measure that
would raise personal or corporate income tax rates, though not for increases
in other taxes.
An even broader change, demanding a three-fifths majority in both the House
and the Senate for any tax increase, is included in the Republicans' draft
of a constitutional amendment requiring a balanced budget.
But while the constitutional amendment itself would require a two-thirds
majority in both chambers of Congress, as well as ratification by three-
quarters of the states, the change to House rules will require only a simple
majority and should pass easily.
</TEXT>
