<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / Counting cost of bankruptcy: Taxpayers will be angry at the
officials who got the county into trouble and at the firms which profited
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The bankruptcy on Tuesday of California's Orange County is without parallel
in the history of American local government. One of the wealthiest counties
in the US, with a population of 2.6m and an annual budget of Dollars 1.5bn
(Pounds 961m), has been forced into default through a game of double or
quits in the financial markets.
In time, the outraged taxpayers of Orange County will want their revenge. It
may extend not merely to the officials who lost Dollars 1.5bn of their
money, but to the Wall Street firms which profited by helping them.
The immediate effects on life in Orange County may be minor. Under the
provisions of Chapter 9 - the type of bankruptcy applying to municipalities
 -the county cannot pay outstanding bills to suppliers or back wages to its
employees, at least until a reorganisation plan has been worked out over
coming months. In the meantime, though, it can pay wages or other bills
incurred since the bankruptcy.
The longer-term effects are another matter. While in bankruptcy, the county
cannot pay income on its bonds. Its credit in the bond markets is thus badly
damaged. Even when it can re-enter the markets, it will have to pay more for
its money.
A hint of what this might mean came yesterday from the county's
transportation authority, which has Dollars 1.1bn invested in the
loss-making central fund. It has assembled a team of specialists 'to address
debt service, payroll and other obligations'.
Its planned mass transit programme, the authority said, should still be able
to go ahead: 'However, it may not be on the same timetable.'
The treasurer of the town of Huntington Beach, which has Dollars 69m
invested in the fund, said yesterday that while the city should be able to
maintain its police and fire services, it would put all non-essential
spending on hold.
Meanwhile, the financial markets are desperately grappling with the event's
complexities. One central point is at issue: whether the banks that hold
securities against Orange County's debts are constrained by its bankruptcy
from selling them.
The whole point of the bankruptcy was to stop holders of the county's
reverse repurchase agreements from liquidating their positions. Yesterday
some banks started selling anyway. If order can be restored, the Dollars
1.5bn loss so far reported on Orange County's Dollars 7.5bn fund may remain
at least partly on paper. If all the banks join the stampede, the losses
will be crystallised and very possibly increased.
In that case, Orange County will be seen to have made a disastrous
miscalculation. Bankruptcy was an extreme measure, which will greatly damage
the county's financial reputation.
If it did not even succeed in its object, it will have been worse than
useless.
Either way, Wall Street will not look good in the public eye. It is already
being pointed out that the broker Merrill Lynch, in particular, was
instrumental in helping county treasurer Mr Robert Citron play the markets.
The company rebutted this vigorously yesterday. Chairman Daniel Tully said:
'We do not believe that we have any legal liability whatsoever, and we would
vigorously contest any such action.'
The firm could doubtless also argue that it is not its job to warn a client,
merely to transact on his behalf. Whether that will carry weight in the
heated aftermath of the Orange County fiasco remains to be seen.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
