<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / Orange County hit by Wall St selling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The affairs of Orange County, the California region which filed for
bankruptcy on Tuesday, appeared in chaos yesterday as Wall Street firms
started selling investments held on the county's behalf.
The move, which the bankruptcy was designed to prevent, risks pushing Orange
County's losses above the Dollars 1.5bn (Pounds 961m) disclosed last week.
Several companies, among them the Japanese bank Nomura, were reported to
have liquidated up to Dollars 500m of reverse repurchase positions. These
are deals whereby Orange County had borrowed up to Dollars 12bn from Wall
Street firms to buy securities, which were then left with the firms as
collateral. On Tuesday some firms, led by CS First Boston, liquidated over
Dollars 1bn of these positions, precipitating Orange County's bankruptcy
later that day.
Orange County said yesterday morning it believed the bankruptcy 'stayed and
enjoined' all creditors from further liquidation of securities held under
reverse repo transactions. However, the Wall Street broker Smith Barney,
which holds Dollars 800m worth of reverse repos, said: 'We dispute the stay.
It doesn't mean we can't liquidate.'
The county filed for bankruptcy under Chapter 9, which applies only to
municipalities. Since there is no precedent for a Chapter 9 case of this
size or complexity, there has been wide confusion over the legal position.
One expert, Mr James Spiotto of Chapman and Cutler, said yesterday that
recent amendments to the municipal bankruptcy statute allowed liquidation of
reverse repos.
The broker Merrill Lynch, which was the county's chief source of finance and
holds Dollars 2bn worth of its repos, said: 'We have not liquidated
collateral or withdrawn any credit extended to the county.' Merrill defended
its role in the collapse, saying it had worked with Orange County for 20
years and had operated in line with its client's published strategies. 'The
client has managed a large portfolio in a sophisticated and public manner,
with above-average returns, for many years.' It denied it had any legal
liability for the bankruptcy.
Last week it emerged that Orange County, under its treasurer Mr Robert
Citron, had incurred paper losses of Dollars 1.5bn on its Dollars 7.5bn fund
as a result of aggressively leveraged investment strategies. Mr Citron
resigned on Monday.
It is not certain that Orange County will be allowed to go bankrupt. In
1991, Bridgeport, Connecticut, sought Chapter 9 protection but a judge
denied it on the grounds that the city was solvent.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
