<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / Clarke lifts rates to reassure City: Major resists pressure
to readmit Tory rebels in wake of defeat over VAT on fuel Chancellor seeks
ways to fund Pounds 1bn shortfall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, PETER NORMAN and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major's government moved swiftly yesterday to retain the confidence
of financial markets in the wake of its latest political crisis by raising
interest rates 0.5 points to 6.25 per cent.
The rise came ahead of an announcement today by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the
chancellor, of a package of spending cuts and possible tax rises to fill the
Pounds 1bn gap left by the enforced scrapping of the second stage of value
added tax on domestic fuel.
In an apparent olive branch to his party's right wing after the recent Tory
infighting over Europe, the prime minister hinted at a possible referendum
on European integration.
Moves towards a single European currency would represent a 'very significant
decision', he said. Speaking on Channel Four news, he insisted that a
referendum could not be used as a tactical device, but added: 'I have not
ruled out a referendum but it is a long way away.'
Amid undisguised jubilation in the opposition parties at the government's
humiliation on Tuesday night, Mr Tony Blair, the Labour leader, said the
Commons defeat marked 'a decisive turn in the political tide'. Mr Paddy
Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, said the government's position was now
irrecoverable.
Mr Major shrugged off suggestions that his government had lost its authority
and dismissed speculation that his leadership was under threat. However, he
implicitly acknowledged that the government might not be able to see out its
full parliamentary term to mid-1997.
But as the government struggled to contain the political fall-out from its
most significant Commons defeat during 15 years in office, there were new
divisions in the Tory party and signs of recriminations in the cabinet.
Mr Major faced strong pressure from the Tory right to readmit to the
parliamentary party the nine Eurosceptic MPs who played a crucial part in
forcing the government to abandon its proposed increase in VAT on fuel from
8 per cent to 17.5 per cent.
Mr Jonathan Aitken, the Treasury chief secretary, said he hoped soon to see
some 'bridge-building', a view shared by other rightwing members of the
cabinet.
In talks with party managers yesterday, Mr Major rejected the idea that the
suspended MPs should be readmitted quickly. However, in a further concession
to Eurosceptic demands, the government avoided further embarrassment on the
European Union finance bill, which triggered the present political storm, by
agreeing to strong measures to curb EU fraud. The government comfortably won
a confidence vote on the third reading of the bill.
There were signs yesterday of disagreement in the cabinet over the events of
the past two weeks. Rightwing MPs said they had been told that Mr Major had
misjudged the mood of the party. In separate criticisms of Mr Clarke's
handling of the VAT issue, there were strong reports, denied by Downing
Street, that the prime minister had been among a handful of ministers who
wanted the chancellor to drop the proposed VAT increase.
Meanwhile, Mr Major's long-standing enemies on the right of the party were
joined by less controversial senior MPs in suggesting that his leadership
now depends on his ability to restore a semblance of unity to the party.
Mr Major himself appeared outwardly unruffled by the latest setback.
Speaking at a breakfast for businessmen, he insisted that the government
would stick firmly to a strategy of low inflation and strong growth.
The base rate increase, which pleased the City but caused dismay among
industry groups and retailers, was decided in the morning by Mr Clarke at
his monthly monetary meeting with Mr Eddie George, the governor of the Bank
of England, and announced immediately afterwards.
Ministers later made clear that the defeat in the Commons had turned an
expected rise in rates into what one termed an 'unavoidable certainty'.
Mr Clarke gave a robust defence of his action in television and radio
interviews. The rate increase, he said, was needed 'to sustain economic
recovery with low inflation', leading to higher living standards and more
jobs. Like his first half-point rate increase in September, it was 'the
right response' to signs of inflationary pressures.
Official figures provided further evidence of the UK economy's fast growth.
The Central Statistical Office said manufacturing output grew a seasonally
adjusted 0.5 per cent in October from September, and was 5.5 per cent up on
October last year.
The City reacted positively to the rate increase but it drew criticism from
industry and commerce. The main mortgage lenders held back from immediate
rate increases.
Mr Tim Melville-Ross, director-general of the Institute of Directors, said
investment would be dearer. Mr Hugh Clark, trading policy director of the
British Retail Consortium, said the rise was 'exceedingly ill-timed'. j
The rate rise underpinned sterling, lifting the pound by  3/4 pfennig to
DM2.4576. It also boosted bonds, with 10-year gilts adding  1/4 point.
However, the FT-SE 100 index closed at 3,012.5, down 3.6.
AFTER THE VAT VOTE
Major's fatal attraction, Page 8
