<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 94 / Spending cuts loom as rates rise: Capital plans face axe to
meet Pounds 1bn shortfall - Chancellor acts to retain confidence of
financial markets with half point increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, PETER NORMAN and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major's government moved swiftly yesterday to hold the confidence of
financial markets in the wake of its latest political crisis by pushing up
interest rates 0.5 points to 6.25 per cent.
The rise came ahead of an announcement today by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the
chancellor, of a package of possible tax rises and spending cuts to fill the
Pounds 1bn gap left by the enforced scrapping of the second stage of
value-added tax on domestic fuel. Ministers expect most if not all of the
shortfall to be made up in spending cuts, with capital programmes a likely
target.
In an apparent olive branch to his party's right wing after the recent Tory
infighting over Europe, the prime minister hinted also at a possible
referendum on European integration.
Moves towards a single European currency would represent a 'very significant
decision', he said. Speaking on Channel Four news, he insisted that a
referendum could not be used as a tactical device, but added: 'I have not
ruled out a referendum but it is a long way away.'
Amid undisguised jubilation in the opposition parties at the government's
humiliation on Tuesday night, Mr Tony Blair, the Labour leader, said the
Commons defeat marked 'a decisive turn in the political tide'. Mr Paddy
Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, said the government's position was now
irrecoverable. Mr Major shrugged off renewed suggestions that the government
had lost its authority. He dismissed speculation that his leadership was
under threat but implicitly acknowledged that the government might not be
able to see out its full term.
But as the government struggled to contain the political fall-out from its
most significant Commons defeat during 15 years in office, there were new
divisions in the Tory party and signs of recriminations in the cabinet.
Mr Major faced strong pressure from the Tory right to readmit to the
parliamentary party the nine Eurosceptic MPs who played a crucial part in
forcing the government to abandon its proposed increase in VAT on fuel from
8 per cent to 17.5 per cent.
The calls for him to retreat over Europe found an echo in comments by Mr
Jonathan Aitken, the Treasury chief secretary. Mr Aitken said he hoped soon
to see some 'bridge-building', a view shared by other right-wing members of
the cabinet.
But the idea that the suspended MPs should be readmitted quickly was flatly
rejected by the prime minister in talks with Tory party managers. He refused
to give any timetable for the rebels' possible re-entry to the parliamentary
party.
Downing Street also slapped down suggestions that Mr Richard Ryder's
position as chief whip might be in doubt in the wake of the VAT-on-fuel
defeat.
There were signs, however, of separate disagreements in the cabinet over the
events of the past two weeks. Rightwing MPs said they had been told that Mr
Major had misjudged the mood of the party.
In separate criticisms of Mr Clarke's handling of the VAT issue, there were
strong reports, denied by Downing Street, that the prime minister had been
among a handful of ministers who wanted the chancellor to drop the proposed
VAT increase.
Outwardly Mr Major himself appeared unruffled. Speaking at a breakfast for
businessmen, he insisted that the government would stick firmly to an
overall economic strategy of low inflation and strong growth.
The base rate increase, which pleased the City but caused dismay among
industry groups and retailers, was decided in the morning by Mr Kenneth
Clarke, the chancellor, at his monthly monetary meeting with Mr Eddie
George, the governor of the Bank of England, and announced immediately
afterwards.
The City reacted positively to the rate increase but it drew criticism from
industry and commerce. The main mortgage lenders, conscious of the weak
housing market, held back from immediate rate increases.
Mr Tim Melville-Ross, director-general of the Institute of Directors, said
investment would be dearer. Mr Hugh Clark, trading policy director of the
British Retail Consortium, which represents 90 per cent of the UK retail
trade, said the rise was 'exceedingly ill-timed and unwelcome', coming in
the middle of the crucial Christmas trading period.
The rate increase underpinned sterling, lifting the pound by  3/4 pfennig to
DM2.4576. It also boosted bonds, with 10-year gilts adding 1/4 point.
However, equities reversed early gains in line with Wall Street, with the
FTSE-100 index closing at 3,012.5, down 3.6.
