<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JEFFREY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stock index futures had a roller-coaster session, sliding steeply during the
morning but clawing back steadily towards the end of the day's trading,
writes Jeffrey Brown.
The FT-SE 100 December contract was at 3,022 at the close of pit trading,
down 19 points. The premium to the cash market was eight points, or more
than six points over fair value.
Sentiment was weak at the close but it had been far blacker during the
morning session when heavy selling pushed the December contract down to a
low for the day of 2,988 in good volume, with some 9,000 contracts dealt by
mid-morning.
There was an eerie lull around midsession but by 2.30pm, when Wall Street
came into the picture, buyers were beginning to emerge.
Traders said the final hour of trading produced a significant squeeze,
hoisting the December contract back above 3,000. In late screen-based
trading the December contract moved up to 3,027. At the official close,
volume totalled 15,800 lots - against 12,683 on Monday - but 2,500 of this
was spread trading into the March contract.
Traded option activity showed a clear bounce, rising to 43,188 lots from
30,168 on Monday. Puts outnumbered calls by more than two-to-one. FT-SE and
Euro FT-SE lots totalled 30,500.
</TEXT>
