<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow little changed after
volatile day
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA BRANSTEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices closed nearly flat after a volatile day that saw stocks
buffeted by negative news and first cheered, then depressed, by climbing
bond prices, writes Lisa Bransten in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 4.03 at 3,745.95.
Secondary indices fell modestly. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 eased 0.21 to
453.11, the American SE composite was off 1.24 at 431.01 and the Nasdaq
composite dipped 4.48 to 741.23. NYSE volume amounted to 300m shares.
The Dow dropped by nearly 20 points in early trading before heading into
positive territory near midday. Analysts speculated that the drop might have
been due to the announcement late on Monday by Fidelity Investments - the
largest mutual fund company in the US - that its Magellan Fund would not
make a previously announced year-end distribution.
Analysts worried that individual investors, who had flocked to mutual funds
in recent years, might shift their investments to fixed income instruments,
where yields were becoming increasingly attractive.
Rising bond prices, however, initially pulled the stock market up, before
exerting some pull on assets, thereby pushing shares to the session's lows
late in the afternoon. The Dow fell more than 25 points before program
trading kicked in and brought the average up just above Monday's close at
the end of the day.
The late-morning resignation of Treasury secretary Lloyd Bentsen went all
but unnoticed by the market because the move had been widely anticipated by
investors.
Among individual shares, BankAmerica lost Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars 40 3/8
after an analyst at Paine-Webber downgraded the shares to 'neutral' from
'buy' on the basis of slower than expected loan growth. Mr Lawrence Cohn
also cut his 1994 earnings estimate by 15 cents to Dollars 5.35 per share.
Other banking stocks were mixed. Chase Manhattan Bank edged up Dollars 1/8
to Dollars 35 5/8 and Citicorp firmed Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 41 5/8 , while
Bank of New York was Dollars  1/8 softer at Dollars 27 3/4 and First Chicago
slipped Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 46 3/8 .
Borden shed Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 13 3/8 after the group rejected
overtures from Mr Paul Kazarian, a would-be suitor for the beleaguered
company.
High-technology shares were mixed. IBM gained Dollars  1/8 at Dollars 71 5/8
, Compaq Computer rose Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 41 5/8 , Apple Computer put
on Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 37 1/2 and Dell Computer hardened Dollars  1/8 to
Dollars 42 3/4 . Hewlett-Packard lost Dollars 1/4 at Dollars 97 1/2 ,
Digital Equipment fell Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 32 3/4 and Unisys eased
Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 9 1/8 .
Canada
Fears of rising interest rates drove Toronto stocks down but the market
ended well above the day's worst after moderate trading. Year-end tax-loss
selling was also contributing to weakness in the market.
The TSE 300 composite index, down nearly 40 points at one stage, finished
17.12 off at 4,079.44. Declines outpaced rises by 488 to 284 after volume of
59m shares.
Eleven of the 14 sub-indices were down, led by conglomerate, oil, industrial
products and financial stocks. Gold, transportation and real estate shares
posted gains.
</TEXT>
