<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / Survey of Zimbabwe (8): High-quality leaves - Tobacco
production
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY HAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After two disastrous seasons in which tobacco prices on the Harare auction
floors plunged more than 60 per cent to US124 cents a kilogram, 1994 was a
much better year for the industry than anyone predicted.
In the early 1990s, production took off in response to a shortlived global
shortage, with volume jumping 68 per cent between 1989 (130m kg) and 1993
(218m kg). Initially, this was accompanied by rising prices, up from US176
cents a kg in 1989 to a record 325 cents in the boom year of 1991 when the
crop was worth Dollars 572m, with exports of Dollars 532m contributing 30
per cent of total foreign earnings.
Farmers raised their plantings but the severe 1992 drought and the
subsequent collapse of world tobacco prices in 1992-93 reversed this
process. The 1994 crop of 169m kg was 22 per cent lower than last year and
the smallest since 1990. Firmer world demand and global production cutbacks
boosted prices on the Harare floors which rose 40 per cent to 173 cents a
kg, little different from 1989 levels.
Exports fell by a third in 1992-93 but have recovered modestly to an
estimated USDollars 400m in 1994.
Tobacco is the country's largest export, accounting for an estimated 22 per
cent of the total.
While the 1991 euphoria has disappeared, the industry is mildly optimistic
about future prospects. The world tobacco market is divided into two - with
the low-value, low-quality segment dominated by Asian producers, especially
China, while the US, Brazil and Zimbabwe are the lead players in the
flavour, high-quality leaf sector. Here demand and supply are in rough
balance, subject to planned sell-off of the US stabilisation stockpile
currently being negotiated.
Zimbabwe producers are optimistic about modest growth - 5 per cent annually
 -in the second half of the decade, targeting planned increases in cigarette
production in Eastern Europe and possibly also China. The Zimbabwe Tobacco
Association, which represents some 1,650 large-scale growers producing over
95 per cent of the crop, has recommended a maximum 7.5 per cent increase in
planting this season.
Given the poor and late start to the rains, growers say crop could exceed
190m kg this year - dry seasons result in larger, though lower quality,
production. Expansion, culminating in lower prices, during the 1990-93
period was a reminder that Zimbabwe's future lies in niche production.
Industry experts urge growers to focus on quality rather than volume, since
Zimbabwe cannot outcompete low-cost producers in Brazil and Asia, especially
China.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
