<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / International Company News: WMX takes control of Ohio-based
group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
International refuse hauler and environmental services company WMX has
further specialised its toxic waste clean-up operations by acquiring a
controlling interest in an Ohio-based group called OHM Corporation. The
deal, an exchange of assets for shares, is valued at about Dollars 75m.
WMX subsidiary Rust International has agreed to swap its hazardous and
nuclear waste remediation services business units, including about 900
employees and specialised hazardous waste treatment equipment, to OHM in
exchange for 10.4m shares, or about 40 per cent, of OHM stock. The
transaction is subject to the approval of shareholders in both companies.
The deal will allow Rust International to focus on its core environmental
services businesses, while giving OHM a dominant position among the small
group of US companies that specialises in cleaning up big hazardous waste
sites under the government-directed Superfund programme.
As part of the transaction, WMX has agreed to provide OHM with low-cost
financing for the next five years. OHM last year had net income of Dollars
4.4m on sales of Dollars 242m.
Mr James Kirk, OHM chairman, said the deal would 'yield a significant
improvement in our financial position and enhance our ability to fund our
growth with access to lower-cost financing'.
After combining Rust's hazardous waste remediation operations, OHM will have
about 3,100 employees, a client portfolio evenly divided between public and
private sectors, and a contract backlog of about Dollars 2.1bn.
</TEXT>
