FT  07 DEC 94 / International Company News: Hawker Siddeley Canada lifts
Orenda
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Hawker Siddeley Canada (HSC) has buttressed the long term expansion of its
Orenda Aerospace Division with a CDollars 230m (USDollars 167m) agreement to
make and service jet engines and parts for GE Aircraft Engines Canada, one
of the world's two biggest jet engine producers.
Orenda repairs and overhauls large jet engines and makes components for both
jets and industrial turbines. It is HSC's biggest single subsidiary. The
others lease railcars and build sawmill, mining and materials handling
equipment.
BTR sold its 59 per cent control of HSC last spring in a CDollars 122m
secondary share offer.
Orenda will become GE Aircraft's designated manufacturer of selected turbine
discs and other parts for three engine series sold worldwide.
The agreement will produce at least CDollars 230m worth of business over 20
years, and could generate further orders by providing access to European and
Middle East markets.
Orenda has already extended operations to the US. It has sold its steel
foundry division in Canada and is struggling to turn round its loss-making
sawmill equipment unit in the US.
The British mining equipment unit is being restructured, while railcar
leasing is highly profitable with booming North American commodity traffic.
</TEXT>
