<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / International Company News: French bank finds few friends -
A look at BCP's tough struggle to steer clear of bankruptcy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For troubled French banks, it helps to be big. While Credit Lyonnais, the
loss-making state-owned bank has received capital injections of more than
FFr5bn (Dollars 925m) to rescue it from sustained and substantial losses,
Banque Commercial Privee, a minnow in comparison, has faced a tougher
struggle in its battle against bankruptcy.
Since the declaration of a cessation of payments on Monday, the Paris-based
bank, which has 1,200 clients, one branch, 50 staff, and which requires an
estimated recapitalisation of FFr140m, has presented France's financial
community with a test of its ability to revive the smaller players in the
financial sector.
'It is the first French bank to close its doors since 1992, when Banque
Majorel failed,' says one French official. He argues that several small
banks have been weakened by the impact of recession in 1992 and 1993 and the
resulting bankruptcies which have continued to rise, in spite of broader
economic recovery this year. 'When you are small, you are more vulnerable.
It is often harder to find a white knight.'
Yesterday, the French banking community moved to reassure BCP's depositors
who have had their accounts frozen since November 21. The Association of
French Banks said it was invoking its so-called, 'solidarity mechanism'
through which its 428 members provide funds to repay up to FFr400,000 per
deposit. This is estimated to involve a cost of about FFr70m.
But whether the bank itself can find relief, however, remains far from
clear.
The Commission Bancaire, the regulatory arm of the Bank of France, the
country's central bank, has sought to bring pressure to bear on BCP's
shareholders to come to its rescue. It has done so through the application
of article 52-1 of the banking law, a provision which calls on shareholders
to provide funds for insolvent financial institutions.
This provision contrasts with article 52-2, under which the whole of the
French banking system is called to the rescue of a troubled bank. This
provision, last used in 1988 for the rescue of the Al-Saudi bank, is invoked
when the image and stability of the French financial system is considered to
be jeopardised.
'This is not the case with BCP,' says one French banker. 'It is not seen as
a big risk to the financial community or a political issue, so the rescue is
being sought through a recourse to shareholders.' For Mr Jean Varda,
appointed as provisional administrator of the bank, it is a vital search.
'It is imperative that we find a shareholder of reference to restore
liquidity and assure survival,' he says.
The problem for BCP, however, is that its shareholders are unable or so far
unwilling to jump into the breach. GAN, the loss-making state-owned insurer,
is one of the biggest investors in UNI, a holding company which controls 86
per cent of the shares of BCP.
However, it has said that it does not feel responsible for BCP and has
increased the plight of the bank by ending its access to the interbanking
market through UIC, GAN's banking division.
Macif, the mutual insurance company which holds 14 per cent of BCP, has
similarly indicated a reluctance to advance fresh capital, while UNI itself
is thought to lack the funds necessary to shore up the balance sheet.
The irony is that many in the banking community believe that the situation
facing BCP is far from terminal. Although it has suffered losses over the
past two years, and has been particularly exposed to the impact of recession
because of its loans to the small business sector, the required
recapitalisation is small compared with the bank's assets of about FFr1.7bn.
'It is not in such bad shape,' says one banking source. 'Liquidation could
be avoided.'
Whether it will be depends partly on a meeting tomorrow of the Paris
Tribunal de Commerce, the capital's commercial court. The meeting will
determine whether to wind up the bank or place it under judicial
redressment, a procedure which grants court appointed administrators six
months to seek a solution for the bank.
For most observers, the latter is the more likely outcome. BCP's client list
may attract potential buyers, while GAN's state shareholder may also exert
pressure on the insurance group to provide the necessary funds. For the
meantime, however, the bank and its depositors face a nail-biting wait.
