<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / UK Company News: Powell Duffryn calls for Pounds 71m -
Expansion of ports activities proposed as profits reach Pounds 17m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Powell Duffryn is proposing to raise Pounds 70.7m net of expenses via a
rights issue, to fund the acquisition of the shares it does not own in
Teesside Holdings and Humberside Holdings.
The specialist engineering, distribution and storage company said the
acquisition would fit in with the corporate strategy of expanding its ports
activities.
Teesside Holdings, which owns Tees and Hartlepool Port Authority, is owned
by a consortium of Powell Duffryn, 3i Group and Humberside Holdings.
Humberside is owned equally by Powell Duffryn and the family of Mr John
Holloway, chief executive of Teesside and a director of Humberside.
The 1-for-4 issue of 16.6m new ordinary shares is priced at 440p and has
been underwritten by SG Warburg. The share price yesterday closed 25p down
at 517p.
Powell Duffryn is planning a total investment of Pounds 98.4m, including an
offer of Pounds 8.6m for the employees' 5 per cent holding in Teesside.
Mr Bill Andrews, chief executive, said about 350 employees were shareholders
and, if they accepted a cash offer of Pounds 18.17 a share, the maximum any
individual would receive would be about Pounds 60,000 before tax.
The group is planning to pay Pounds 82.3m for the acquisitions, of which
Pounds 12m is in the form of loan notes, Pounds 7.5m in Powell Duffryn
shares and the balance in cash. In addition, the vendors of Humberside will
receive a cash dividend of Pounds 7.5m.
The rights issue and acquisitions are subject to shareholder approval and an
extraordinary general meeting will be held on December 29.
Powell Duffryn said its investment, made in early 1992, had been 'extremely
successful'. Teesside made a pre-tax profit of Pounds 13.6m in the year to
end-March.
Humberside Holdings, which runs services at east coast ports including
Immingham, Hull and Grimsby, made a pre-tax profit of Pounds 6.7m in the
year to end-March.
Mr David Hubbard, chairman, said pro-forma gearing after the rights issue
would be about 30 per cent, which he described as 'very comfortable'.
The group also announced an advance in pre-tax profits from Pounds 10.3m to
Pounds 17m on turnover up by Pounds 8.8m to Pounds 354m for the six months
to end-September.
The pre-tax outcome, however, included a profit of Pounds 2.2m (Pounds 5.7m
deficit) from discontinued activities.
The interest charge was cut to Pounds 1.8m (Pounds 2.6m) and earnings came
out at 17.8p (8.2p) - or 15p (14.1p) excluding exceptionals. The interim
dividend is being raised to 8p (6.6p).
Mr Hubbard said: 'With some exceptions, trading throughout the group
continues to show the benefits of the steady improvement now evident in the
UK and US economies.'
</TEXT>
