<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / UK Company News: Hazlewood halved at Pounds 10.7m - Problems
at four plants, now solved, cost group Pounds 7m in first half
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Problems at four UK plants helped to halve Hazlewood Foods interim profits.
Mr John Simons, the former finance director who took over as UK chief
executive in September, said yesterday that the problems had cost the group
Pounds 7m. However, all four problem areas had now been sorted out.
Pre-tax profits for the six months to October 1 fell from Pounds 23.3m to
Pounds 10.7m, while total sales grew from Pounds 403.9m to Pounds 426.1m.
Excluding exceptionals, profits were Pounds 12.1m (Pounds 25.6m). Sales from
continuing operations were ahead from Pounds 390.9m to Pounds 414m.
The group said it had returned two of the problem plants to profit - the
Sheffield sausage factory and the Wrexham ready meals plant. The Hilliers
plant in Plymouth, which makes chilled pies and quiches, was breaking even
at the end of the half following losses which at one time hit Pounds 90,000
a week. The salad processor in Waltham Abbey was sold.
'We made a small loss in the first quarter,' said Mr Simons. 'But we have
come back to substantial profitability after taking these actions.'
Produce was the only one of the group's eight operating divisions to show an
increase in operating profits and margins, making Pounds 5m (Pounds 3.3m) on
sales of Pounds 35.4m (Pounds 37.8m).
The ready meals division fell into the red to the tune of Pounds 1.1m,
compared with a profit of Pounds 6.3m. The result was hit by the Wrexham
plant problems, a depressed ice cream market, and raw material costs at Fri
D'Or, the Dutch potato processor.
The non-food division, which makes nappies and other paper goods, was also
hit by raw material increases which sent it Pounds 100,000 into the red
(Pounds 1.5m profit).
Grocery division profits fell to Pounds 1.9m (Pounds 4.3m), hit by price
rises of up to 50 per cent for soft fruit for jam making, and by a falling
market for pickles.
Mr Simons said the group had now tidied up most of the peripheral problems,
and had established itself as a strong competitor in the convenient food and
ready meal markets. 'The team is very confident that this will lead to a
better second half performance.'
Earnings a share fell from 6.94p to 3.27p. The interim dividend is unchanged
at 2.4p.
COMMENT
The past 12 months have been traumatic for Hazlewood. Its response to
mounting problems has been reasonably rapid, and its has brought in new
blood and attacked its cost base. After a great deal of work, the group is
climbing out of the hole it dug for itself. But the pressures will continue,
not least from raw material price increases, particularly in packaging. The
trouble appears to be that the group is a hotch-potch of relatively small
businesses, with no critical mass in any single one, although it will argue
that 60 per cent of sales now come from the targetted ready meals sector.
Profit forecasts for the full year range from Pounds 29m to Pounds 39m, so
it is probably now best considered as a yield stock. An unchanged dividend
gives a yield of 8 per cent, which is below that of the similarly struggling
Albert Fisher.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Hazlewood Foods.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2011 Meat Packing Plants.
    P2013 Sausages and Other Prepared Meats.
</IN>
