<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / UK Company News: Strategy to protect future expansion plans
at Sturge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, Insurance Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sturge, one of Lloyd's biggest managing agencies, is to set up a new holding
company in an attempt to protect future expansion plans against legal action
threatened by lossmaking members of the insurance market.
The announcement came as the group announced a fall in pre-tax profits,
after stripping out lossmaking discontinued operations, to Pounds 3.06m in
the year to September 30 from Pounds 4.42m. Sturge Holdings also includes
Wise Speke, the private client stockbroker.
Last month the Sturge Names' Action Group, representing more than 3,000
Lloyd's members, said it would issue writs in January seeking compensation
for heavy losses incurred in the early 1990s on Sturge-run insurance
syndicates. SNAG said its claims might eventually total Pounds 1bn.
Lord Poole, Sturge's chief executive, said any action would be resisted
vigorously and that SNAG had little chance of winning.
He said the new holding company could not shield existing businesses from
legal action, but Sturge wanted to expand its range of businesses in the
financial services sector and the new holding company, Ockham Holdings,
would be clearly distanced from the Lloyd's insurance market.
He said any 'cunning ruse' to avoid litigation costs would have been stopped
by the High Court, which has to approve the transfer of Sturge shareholders'
interests into the new company. Separately, Sturge Holdings has increased
its provisions against litigation by Pounds 700,000 to Pounds 5m.
SNAG said it would seek to 'thwart any attempt to stop proper restitution of
assets that have been purloined from Names'.
The annual figures show the heavy cost of Sturge's discontinued members'
agencies, which act for individual members, and recorded an operating loss
of Pounds 2.93m against a loss of Pounds 3.28m last time.
The on-going members' agencies business was sold in October for an initial
consideration of Pounds 500,000. In relation to the disposal, Sturge wrote
off Pounds 12m in goodwill and made a provision for future losses of Pounds
3.78m.
Turnover on continuing operations fell to Pounds 21.6m (Pounds 27.7m).
Earnings per share for continuing operations were 3.9p (7p). Including
discontinued operations, losses per share were 31.1p against earnings of
1.5p. The final dividend is maintained at 2p making 3p for the year.
</TEXT>
