<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / Blow to Clinton as Bentsen quits: President nominates Rubin
to take over US Treasury post
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton is to nominate Mr Robert Rubin as Treasury secretary,
taking over from Mr Lloyd Bentsen, the administration's elder statesman, who
announced his resignation yesterday.
Mr Rubin, a former co-chairman of Goldman Sachs, the Wall Street investment
bank, heads the National Economic Council, a White House policy
co-ordination unit.
Mr Bentsen, 73, who on Monday had called speculation on his departure
'premature', said he had told Mr Clinton in September that he wanted to step
down.
His leaving is not expected to signal any sharp change in economic policy.
Mr Rubin and Mr Bentsen stand on the conservative wing of the Democratic
party and share a commitment to free trade, fiscal responsibility and
pro-business policies.
However, after last month's devastating defeat for Democrats in the
congressional elections, the loss of Mr Bentsen, who will return to Texas to
relaunch his business career, is expected to be sorely felt.
One of the criticisms most frequently levelled at Mr Clinton's White House
is its failure to persuade Congress of its way of thinking. That task will
be harder with Republican majorities in the Senate and the House of
Representatives.
With six years' service in the House and 22 in the Senate - the last six as
chairman of the powerful finance committee - Mr Bentsen had an instinct for
Congress's mood and an ability to work with the Republicans that was rare in
the Clinton administration.
Mr Rubin's confirmation by the Senate is not expected to pose difficulties.
He was endorsed yesterday by Senator Robert Dole, the Republican leader in
the Senate, and by Senator Pete Domenici, who will chair the budget
committee.
But Mr Bentsen's retirement still leaves Mr Clinton with a large array of
vacancies to fill. A successor must be found to Mr Rubin at the NEC - the
most widely mentioned candidate is Mr Erskine Bowles, an investment banker.
Mr Clinton also still needs to pick a successor to Mr Mike Espy, who
resigned as agriculture secretary over charges of ethics violations. The
Democrats' political apparatus is also in disarray after last month's poll
setback. Mr Clinton needs to fill the jobs of White House political
director, head of the Democratic National Committee and head of his own
re-election committee.
Honest broker, Page 3
Currencies, Page 40
</TEXT>
