<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / The Lex Column: Siebe
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Siebe has been promising organic growth for some time. Yesterday it produced
some. The controls group has yet to reach its target of increasing sales
from existing operations by 10 per cent. But organic growth in the half year
to end-September was 7.2 per cent and orders were up 13.4 per cent - meaning
Siebe should achieve its goal for the second half. Operating margins were
slightly up despite low margins at some recently acquired companies. In
time, these should rise towards Siebe's 14 per cent average.
The strength of Siebe's business is shown by its return on net assets which
has moved over 26 per cent. The group benefits from operating in markets
which are growing fairly quickly but which are protected by high barriers to
entry. Siebe's high levels of research and capital spending should enable it
to increase its market share steadily without suffering an erosion of
margins.
With annual cash flow of about Pounds 100m and gearing at the half year down
to 19 per cent, Siebe is well-placed to keep up a steady flow of infill
acquisitions. So far, it has shown itself adept at integrating new
purchases. If Siebe also confirms in coming months its capacity to grow
organically, its shares will deserve more than the slight market premium on
which they now trade.
</TEXT>
