<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / Game beyond patience
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOE ROGALY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government can go on like this. Alas, it probably will. The question is
 -for how long? Yesterday the answer might have been clear. The assumption
was that the Conservative term that began in April 1992 would last the full
five years, if the party managers thought they could improve their chances
of winning the next election by hanging on. That assumption is now history.
Mr John Major can no longer bank on a full term. He is the plaything of
fate. He cannot credibly aspire to be the master of events. His
administration is not about to fall, but it is increasingly unsteady on its
feet.
We could, therefore, be in for an indefinite period of unstable government,
one that should go but nevertheless stays. It is only when - if - a ministry
is forced to abandon its budgetary stance that it can be said to have failed
absolutely. In such circumstances it is obliged to resign. As matters rest,
the prime minister can hold on, hoping for a turn in the Conservatives'
political fortunes. His strategies may appear in ruins - a familiar sight -
but in theory he could recover.
Mr Major was careful to establish that the vote he lost last night was not a
matter of confidence. He was, of course, technically correct. Labour's
successful motion merely amended the parliamentary procedure for handling
this year's finance bill. The Chancellor's sensible response to the vote was
instantly to throw in his losing hand, and it should not take too much
imagination for him to come up tomorrow with substitute taxes or further
expenditure cuts to plug the financial gap.
But in the real world of contemporary politics, nothing is that simple. The
government was knocked sideways in September 1992, when, on Black Wednesday,
sterling was summarily ejected from the European exchange rate mechanism.
That set off a downward spiral of political misfortune from which the
administration has spasmodically managed to extricate itself, always to fall
back into a hole shortly afterwards.
Mr Major may go down in history as the Phoenix with nine lives. He is ever
picking himself up, always to be slammed over again.
Every Conservative knows why. The party, divided on Europe before Black
Wednesday, became more deeply schismatic after that searing experience. Most
of its leaders achieved political maturity during the 1980s, when the Tories
enjoyed 100-plus majorities. They have found Parliament more difficult to
manage with the small and dwindling majority won in spring 1992. Mr Major
would have resigned a few months later if he had lost the vote on the bill
to ratify the Maastricht treaty, or last week if he had failed to win the
vote on an increase in European Union funds. The government shrank from
privatising the Post Office because, as it admitted, it did not command the
necessary parliamentary support.
It is moving in a world of shifting coalitions, familiar in other European
countries and the US, but alien to the English mind. Whitehall is horrified
at the prospect of power sharing. Yet on one issue the government must gain
the support of Ulster Unionists; on a second it must declare a vote of
confidence to avoid defeat; on a third it is obliged to engineer a further
turn of the ratchet towards the Eurosceptics. Mr Major's posture on the EU,
his arms around its heart while he kicks it in the shins, is increasingly
difficult to sustain. Mr Kenneth Clarke's cunning Budget plan, building up
indirect taxes today in order to bribe the voters with cuts in income tax
next year, would make sense if the Tories were united, but plainly they are
not.
Previous lost budgetary votes are an unreliable guide to what happens now.
Labour lost a clutch of them in 1977. It was turfed out two years later.
In 1981 Lord Howe, then chancellor, raised several taxes, but was defeated
by a Labour amendment that deleted an increase in the duty on diesel. He
responded by increasing other imposts. Yet the most triumphant years of the
Thatcher government of which he was then a pillar followed.
Mr Major's present situation undoubtedly bears a closer resemblance to that
of the Callaghan administration of 1978-79 than it does to the Thatcher
ministry of the early 1980s. The last Labour government struggled on, with
the help of Ulster votes, past everyone's patience. It is possible, but
increasingly less likely, that the Tories will manage to do the same.
</TEXT>
<XX>
