<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
You can share two very different trips tonight. In Great Journeys (9.30pm
BBC2) the young Scots timpanist Evelyn Glennie travels through Korea in
search of the country's musical roots. The Korean paradox - an ancient
culture combined with a booming economy and ruthless western modernisation -
leaves her with the suspicion of a tourist-conscious heritage industry
artificially kept alive and swamping the real thing (it sounds familiar).
After noting Confucianism and Buddhism, Glennie decides that Shamanism, the
worship of spirits, embodies the true Korea. We leave her on the seashore
with a beautifully photographed Shaman ceremony and an interview with 'the
Kiri Te Kanawa' of Korean opera, where a song can last 12 hours.
Specialised perhaps, but Glennie's unself-conscious enthusiasm gives it
integrity. Travelog (8.30pm Channel 4) is as synthetic as its title. A
former stand-up comic goes mechanically through the motions; whether in
Cyprus or Hungary the cliches come thick and fast.
</TEXT>
