<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / Motor industry alarmed as private sales decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A further sharp fall last month in the number of new cars purchased has
caused increasing alarm in the UK motor trade that private buyers are
deserting the market in growing numbers.
Industry officials yesterday described last month's 13.5 per cent fall in
the number of new cars bought privately, compared with November 1993, as
another indication of the UK's faltering economic recovery and lack of
consumer confidence.
However, a further strong rise in commercial vehicle registrations last
month - of 17.13 per cent year-on-year - and a 15.7 per cent rise in fleet
car registrations, is seen by some analysts as a sign that the industry may
have to look elsewhere to explain the steep fall-off in private buyers
during recent months.
They suggest that prices higher than private buyers consider justified,
followed by rapid depreciation - caused in part by manufacturers giving
priority to the fleet market - are leading private customers to opt for
low-mileage used cars.
Mr Alan Pulham, director of the National Franchised Dealers Association, has
criticised manufacturers' pricing policies and the fact that cars are mainly
designed for the business car market. Overall, he says, the price of a
medium-sized family car is about Pounds 2,000 higher than it would be
otherwise, and values on the used market have been undermined by deeply
discounted sales to fleets.
Prof Garel Rhys, professor of motor industry economics at Cardiff Business
School, has warned that many private buyers may not return to the new car
market until prices fall nearer to North American levels, which are as much
as 40 per cent lower than in the UK.
Statistics from HPI, the vehicle finance monitoring organisation, also show
credit purchases of used cars rising by 11. l per cent in the first nine
months of this year - almost twice the new car level.
Manufacturers have expressed concern privately about the trend, but publicly
insist that the problem is one of confidence.
Mr Ernie Thompson, chief executive of the Society of Motor Manufacturers and
Traders, said yesterday: 'The continuing decline in the retail market in
November continues to demonstrate how fragile consumer confidence remains.'
Ford continues to dominate the list of best-selling cars, with the Escort,
Mondeo and Fiesta occupying the top three places, in spite of production
cuts at the Dagenham and Ellesmere Port plants.
New car registration statistics published by the Society of Motor
Manufacturers and Traders yesterday show Ford was market leader last month,
with a 21.83 per cent share, slightly up from the same period last year. Its
share for the first 11 months of the year has also improved marginally,
opening a gap of nearly 6 percentage points over second-place Vauxhall,
whose share fell by nearly one point.
