<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / Defiant Clarke pledges to maintain recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, told the Commons last night that the
package of taxation measures and public spending cuts he would unveil
tomorrow would ensure that the strength of the economic recovery was
sustained.
Ignoring cries of 'resign' from jeering Labour MPs he made it clear that the
proposals would fill the gap in his Budget calculations resulting from the
government's dramatic eight-vote defeat (319-311). The result meant Labour
had succeeded in its bid to prevent the planned increase from 8 per cent to
17.5 per cent value added tax on domestic fuel from April.
The Conservative MPs who voted against the government were: Mr Michael
Carttiss, Mr Paul Marland, Mr Tony Marlow, Mr Richard Shepherd, Mr David
Sumberg, Mrs Ann Winterton, and Mr Nicholas Winterton.
Tories who abstained were: Mr Phil Gallie, Mr Christopher Gill, Sir Richard
Body, Sir Rhodes Boyson, Mrs Teresa Gorman, Mr William Powell, Sir Teddy
Taylor and Mr John Wilkinson.
Jubilant Labour MPs cheered when Mr Clarke undertook to include a clause in
the forthcoming finance bill to hold the VAT on domestic fuel at the 8 per
cent rate.
He said his package of measures to fill the gap caused by Labour's
'opportunistic' manoeuvre would be designed to ensure that the scheduled
reduction in the public sector borrowing requirement remained on course.
Mr Clarke said: 'Proceeding in that way is essential to keep this recovery
on course to achieve the prosperity and jobs we need in this country.'
Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, said the move to increase VAT on
domestic had been stopped dead in its tracks. He described it as a
'humiliating defeat' for the cabinet, for the chancellor and for Mr John
Major, the prime minister.
Mr Brown said VAT should never have been imposed on domestic fuel in the
first place in view of the pledges given by the prime minister that its
scope would not be extended.
Mr Major gestured in irritation when Mr Brown insisted that 'promises made
by political parties at elections should be kept'.
The shadow chancellor told protesting Tory backbenchers that they would have
to listen to the British people. He said that the government's defeat
signalled a turning point in British politics.
To further Labour cheers he said: 'The Conservative party may remain in
office. But they are tired. They are discredited and they are out of touch.'
Ministers scoffed when Mr Brown said that it was the Labour party that now
represented and spoke for the people of Britain.
Mr Clarke rejected a suggestion by Mr Brown that he should consult
opposition leaders before reaching decisions about the package of proposals
to be unveiled tomorrow.
Backed by government cheers the chancellor said that the failure of Labour
MPs to produce any practical proposals to replace the revenue lost by
keeping VAT on domestic fuel at 8 per cent showed that they were 'utterly
unfitted to take forward the affairs of this country'.
Mr Clarke said Labour MPs had been irresponsible as well as opportunistic in
defeating the government. 'They may gloat today, but we have the
responsibility of keeping British industry on course tomorrow,' he said.
Mr Malcolm Bruce, Liberal Democrat Treasury spokesman, said the government
had suffered a 'monumental rejection' of its policies. A discredited
government had been rejected by the Commons and it should get out, he said.
</TEXT>
