<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / Celebrities line up for road protest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Protest groups fighting proposals to build or widen roads across
environmentally sensitive land and near houses are signing up celebrity
support across the country.
The Department of Transport's plan to build an 11-mile stretch of dual
carriageway close to the existing A27 north of Lewes in East Sussex is one
proposal which has attracted much celebrity support.
Designed to facilitate east-west traffic, particularlycoming off the M23
around Brighton and Lewes, it will cut through the South Downs, an area of
outstanding natural beauty.
The 1,000-member A27 Action Group, formed in January, counts among its
backers Sir Dirk Bogarde, the actor, Lord Healey, the former chancellor of
the exchequer, and Lord Skidelsky, the economist and political historian.
With such heavyweight opponents the road's backers, which include East
Sussex County Council and local chambers of commerce, will have their work
cut out in the publicity war.
The road is on the DoT's priority two list, so it may not be built for ten
years. A public inquiry is not likely for another two years at least.
Mr Nick Davies, secretary of the A27 Action Group, said the road would cost
Pounds 70m and be the biggest construction project ever in the area.' It
would cause considerable damage to our homes, our countryside and our
health,' he said.
He said that there had already been too much development along the south
coast and disputed the economic case for the development.
Mr Bob Wilkins, East Sussex county engineer, rejected comparisons with
Twyford Down, where the M3 extension was the subject of a bitter protest.
He said: 'There is not a physical cut through the downs like there was at
Twyford. The road will run around the side of Mount Cabourn. It will be a
dual carriageway, not a superhighway. It will not be lit along the route, as
critics have suggested. It is true there will be an elevated ramp going up
to 35 feet. But this will be of short duration. Proper landscaping could
make the ramp unobtrusive.'
The county council wants the extension to help with tourism - the county's
main industry - and to help fill a number of small industrial estates.
Mr Robert Caffyn, a local industrialist, has written: 'Tourists enjoy
Eastbourne when they arrive but complain bitterly about the last part of the
journey. Large employers have left the town largely because of poor access.'
The council says that the A27 is dangerous, with too much traffic, too many
blind bends and too many accidents. It said that in the first six months of
the year the number of accidents doubled compared with the same period of
last year.
Mr Davies agreed that the road was dangerous and inadequate. 'But that does
not mean you have to build a new road,' he said. Black spots could be
converted to dual carriageway 'as an interim measure'.
</TEXT>
