<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / Minister faces legal challenge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government faces a further embarrassing legal challenge to a ministerial
decision following a High Court ruling yesterday.
Two sisters who had murder convictions quashed because their trial was
prejudiced by press coverage were granted leave to seek a judicial review of
the solicitor-general's decision not to bring contempt proceedings against
the newspapers involved.
Michelle and Lisa Taylor were jailed for life at the Old Bailey in July 1992
for the murder of bank clerk Alison Shaughnessy. Their convictions were
quashed by the Court of Appeal last June.
The judges ordered the trial papers to be sent to Sir Nicholas Lyell,
attorney-general, to consider contempt proceedings against The Sun, Daily
Mirror, Daily Star and Daily Express. Sir Derek Spencer, solicitor-general,
acting for Sir Nicholas, decided proceedings were 'not appropriate'.
Mr Justice Schiemann, giving leave to the sisters to challenge that
decision, rejected the government argument that, because of the
attorney-general's unique role as 'guardian of the public interest', his
decisions could not be reviewed by the High Court.
Mr Geoffrey Robertson QC, counsel for the sisters, told the judge it was the
first occasion in British history when a court had ruled that defendants
were denied the right to a fair trial as a result of prejudicial press
coverage.
Mr Robertson said it was the sisters' concern that the same thing might
happen again and that others might suffer as they had suffered if the
attorney-general did not act.
Prejudicial material which was inadmissible in court might be published  -
as in the sisters' case - 'and so the danger of trial by newspaper will
become a reality', he said.
</TEXT>
