<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / FT Conferences: BT urges end of support for telecoms rivals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Preferential support for new contenders in the telecommunications market
should be abandoned soon, Sir Iain Vallance, British Telecommunications
chairman, said yesterday.
Speaking on the first day of a Financial Times conference, he said: 'I am
not suggesting limits or controls on market entry. But I am suggesting that
the phase of preferential support for new entrants may soon be ready to
close.'
He also looked forward to deregulated telecoms markets elsewhere in Europe,
arguing that there was a need to develop a 'common and converging'
regulatory framework worldwide.
Sir Iain was speaking a day before the publication by Oftel, the telecoms
regulator, of a consultative document that is expected to precipitate a
fierce debate about the role of regulation in the UK industry.
Since BT was privatised a decade ago a variety of devices have been employed
to protect newcomers from BT's market power and promote competition. The
most important instruments are regulations to keep call prices up and access
prices down. BT is prevented by means of an agreed formula from raising
prices overall. At present the cap is the retail prices index minus 7 1/2
percentage points.
Sir Iain said there should be three specific milestones towards a new
regime:
A commitment to deregulate all retail price activity from 1997. Specific
time limitations on any remaining market entry supports.
A stable and explicit regime for interconnection services that applies to
all licensed network operators.
At present competing operators pay BT a fee for interconnection to its
network to route calls to their eventual destination. The way the
interconnection charge is calculated has been challenged by BT's
competitors.
</TEXT>
