<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / Nolan to probe NHS and House of Lords
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Nolan committee on standards in public life will include National Health
Service trusts and the House of Lords among three 'key areas' in its first
report, to be published next spring.
They will be examined alongside the more widely expected subjects of the
lobbying and financial interests of MPs, and the rules governing the conduct
of ministers and civil servants.
The committee, established by Mr John Major after October's 'cash for
questions' row in the House of Commons, will take written and oral evidence
in the new year.
Lord Nolan, a law lord, said he expected the oral hearings to be in public,
and the committee intended to study overseas practice - particularly recent
moves to regulate abuse of public office in France, the US, Ireland and
Australia, especially Queensland.
He said the three main areas to be covered by the first report would be:
Parliament, including 'cash for questions' in the Commons and the role of
lobbyists. In October controversy about this caused the resignation of Mr
Neil Hamilton and Mr Tim Smith from the government.
Ministers and civil servants - notably the acceptance of gifts, possible
conflicts of interest, and employment on leaving office, issues raised by
cases of former ministers and civil servants taking jobs with companies for
which they were responsible in government.
The 'big spending quangos', including NHS trusts, where the committee will
examine methods of appointment, possible conflicts of interest and standards
of conduct.
The inclusion of NHS trusts in the first report reflects sustained
controversy in the past year about the appointment of leading Conservatives
to the boards of NHS trusts, and their level of remuneration.
The inclusion of the House of Lords was less widely expected. One member of
the committee, Lord Thomson of Monifieth, a former Labour minister, said the
committee would examine the case for obliging peers to enter their outside
financial concerns in a register of interests akin to that used in the
Commons.
By convention peers declare relevant financial interests at the beginning of
speeches in the Lords, but the upper house has no formal register. A move to
introduce one would be highly controversial, particularly among Tory peers,
many of whom are company directors.
The committee yesterday published a note raising the questions it intended
to address. It noted on the issue of MPs' pay and outside interests that the
level of parliamentary salaries 'is in itself not a matter for us', but
added: 'Our task is to consider whether the present relationship between
MPs' parliamentary responsibilities and their outside interests gives rise
to difficulties, and if so whether changes are needed.'
Lord Nolan said the committee would not tackle areas such as local
government, universities and the honours system until the initial report was
completed.
</TEXT>
