<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / Scottish spending plan is criticised
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday described the 1994-95 public spending settlement
for Scotland as an increase, while the opposition attacked it as a cut in
real terms.
Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, told the Commons the Pounds 14.25bn
settlement was an increase of about Pounds 250m on this year's spending and
1 per cent higher than previous plans. The 'very fair' settlement amounted
to more Pounds 6,200 for every home in Scotland.
Mr George Robertson, shadow Scottish secretary, said total spending over the
next three years would fall by more than 4 per cent in real terms. He warned
that jobs and services would be cut.
Comparing the spending plans with those for Wales, Northern Ireland and
England, he complained that Scotland was being 'short-changed yet again'.
The settlement was 'nothing short of a personal humiliation' for Mr Lang and
a 'hammer-blow for Scotland'.
Mr Lang said that thanks to lower inflation, spending power in 1995-96 would
be 2.5 per cent higher than expected. But the government could not let that
'feed through into a higher level of real spending without jeopardising' the
broader objectives of sustained growth.
Apart from the Scottish Prison Service, which would get extra cash, the cost
of running other departments would fall over the next three years by more
than 10 per cent.
Mr Lang was 'tightening up aspects of the capital control regime', and from
April next year notional receipts from the lease of assets to third parties
would not entitle councils to extra capital spending.
But with capital spending from all sources likely to exceed Pounds 1.2bn
next year, the resources available to local authorities for investment
remained substantial.
Mr Lang also said education spending would exceed Pounds 1.35bn next year
and Pounds 1.8bn would go on industry, enterprise and training over the next
three years.
</TEXT>
