FT  07 DEC 94 / South Korean jailed for bribery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Ahn Byong-hwa, a former South Korean state utility chairman, was
sentenced yesterday to three years in prison for receiving bribes in
connection with a multi-billion dollar nuclear power project. The heads of
three conglomerates involved in the 1990 project were also found guilty of
giving bribes to Mr Ahn and received a suspended 10-month prison sentence
each. A three-judge court said the business leaders were given lenient
sentences in consideration of their contribution to the nation's economic
development.
Mr Ahn, who served as president of the state-run Korea Electric Power in
1989-92, was charged with receiving Dollars 1.1m in bribes in connection
with a Dollars 2bn nuclear power project. The three business leaders
involved are Mr Kim Woo-joong of the Daewoo group, Mr Choi Won-suk of the Mr
Dong Ah group and Mr Park Ki-suk of Samsung Construction a construction arm
of the giant Samsung group. The outcome came as a surprise in a country
where businessmen usually maintain close ties with the government. Few
business leaders have been punished in the past although some have been
found involved in corruption and other scandals.
