<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / Patience runs out in S Africa: A look at grievances over
living conditions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK SUZMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As so often in the past, downtown Johannesburg on Monday night was the scene
of violent confrontation between angry black demonstrators and police. But
unlike the clashes of earlier years, this was no clear-cut battle between
the heartless enforcers of apartheid and their defiant victims.
Instead, it was triggered by police evicting homeless people who had
illegally occupied a vacant building in protest at the government's seeming
inability to find them alternative accommodation.
Images of destitute families thrown out on to the street encapsulate a cruel
moral and practical dilemma for the African National Congress-led
government: how can it cater to the demands of its long-suffering black
constituents while reintroducing a culture of law and order?
'Disaffection is growing,' says Mr David Maepa, a local government expert
with First National Bank. 'People are willing to wait if they know something
is being done, but the impression the government gives is of talk and no
action.'
Part of the problem is a crisis in local government across the country. On
everything from the provision of housing to the building of schools, the ANC
has insisted communities should be directly involved; the problem is that as
yet, there exist no post-apartheid local authorities qualified or equipped
to assume such roles.
'At national level, the legitimacy crisis was solved (through the April
elections) before delivery (on black expectations). At local level, the
problems of legitimacy and delivery will have to be confronted at the same
time,' Mr Frederik van Zyl Slabbert, the veteran political analyst charged
with running new local government elections, said in a recent article.
The problem is unlikely to be resolved soon. A year ago, constitutional
negotiators confidently predicted the first democratic local elections would
take place by the end of November. Six months later, the new government put
this date back by a year for logistical reasons, but retained the beginning
of December as the target for integrating white towns and black townships
into single metropolitan councils.
But fewer than half all municipalities have managed even this task,
necessary before voters' rolls can be compiled. The likelihood of elected
authorities taking over before 1996 is receding rapidly.
The corrosive rent and services boycotts that began during the mid-1980s as
a form of political protest are exacerbating the problem by leaving local
bodies short of the funds to undertake development.
As a result, although the cabinet has agreed to write off tenant arrears to
the end of January 1994, at the cost of several billion rands, the strain on
national finances has forced it to insist that payments due from February
onwards must be met in full, a sum that already amounts to R324m in the
so-called PWV area around Johannesburg alone.
While both national and regional ANC leaders are threatening tough action,
including politically unpopular evictions if payments are not met, they are
coming under fire from grassroots organisations. The South African National
Civic Organisation, an umbrella body for the ANC-aligned civic associations
that sprang up in the mid-1980s as alternatives to official government
bodies, has called on the government to scrap all arrears and further cut
the already subsidised rent for township dwellers.
'Basic services must first be guaranteed and an affordable rate needs to be
negotiated with the people,' says Mr Mbongeni Ngubeni, head of Sanco's local
government unit.
Some residents say the time for boycotts has passed, but most chafe at
paying before services are upgraded. 'Why should people pay for faulty
houses and an unreliable water supply?' asks one angry inhabitant of Soweto,
the black township near Johannesburg.
Eskom, the electricity utility, supports the view that improved services
would lead to a higher level of payments, and says that since it upgraded
its infrastructure in Soweto and began an educational and promotional
programme in the area, revenues have risen.
'In October, 40 per cent of residents paid their bills compared to only 26
per cent in September,' says Mr Martin Opperman, the company's negotiations
manager.
As the squatters' protest this week indicated, patience is likely to run out
unless there is a visible effort to address popular grievances well before
the oft-postponed local elections take place. 'They have been sending the
wrong signals so far,' says First National's Mr Maepa. 'It is time for the
government to start addressing grassroots concerns.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ZAZ  South Africa, Africa.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9229 Public Order and Safety, NEC.
    P9121 Legislative Bodies.
</IN>
