<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / ADB approves Kazakh loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MANILA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Asian Development Bank has approved its first two loans, totalling
Dollars 60m, to the central Asian republic of Kazakhstan, the bank said
yesterday. The bank said the loans to Kazakhstan is designed to help it in
the transition to a market-based economy. A Dollars 554,000 technical
assistance grant comes with the loans. The loans will support the
government's stabilisation and structural reform programme by helping bridge
an external financing gap to prevent a further decline in output and
deterioration of living standards, the bank said. The project, which will
promote trade with other countries in the former Soviet Union, is also
intended to ease shortage in foreign exchange for critical imports and allow
firms to access foreign currencies.
The Manila-based bank also approved a Dollars 27.7m loan to improve water
resources in Indonesia to help it enhance capacity at national, provincial,
district and river-basin levels for sustainable and economic management and
use of water resources. The bank said that in recent years water resources
have diminished and growing urbanisation and industrialisation have led to a
deterioration in water supply and quality. AP, Manila
</TEXT>
