FT  07 DEC 94 / BT challenges Sprint alliance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Telecom, the UK's principal telephone operator, yesterday asked the
US Federal Communications Commission to withhold regulatory approval of an
alliance between a large US operator and French and German telephone groups.
It complained that the French and German markets were neither liberalised
nor effectively regulated and that the alliance - called Atlas and involving
Sprint, the US's third largest carrier, together with state-owned France
Telecom and Deutsche Bundespost Telekom - should not receive approval until
equivalence was reached with the US and UK, the world's most liberated
telecoms markets.
Atlas's aim is to provide telecoms facilities to large multinational
companies. BT is already active in this market through an alliance with MCI,
the second largest US long-distance carrier, called Concert. Sprint and its
allies had argued that, in the wake of the BT/MCI approval, the regulatory
process for Atlas could be foreshortened. BT also asked the FCC to look at
European alliances involving AT&amp;T of the US and state-owned companies from
Switzerland and the Netherlands.
