<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 94 / Adams expects US fund-raising ban to be lifted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, expressed confidence he would soon
be allowed to raise funds for his organisation in the US after a meeting at
the White House yesterday with President Bill Clinton's top foreign policy
adviser, reports George Graham from Washington.
'We're satisfied it will be resolved and resolved in a satisfactory way,' he
said. As a condition of his current visa to the US, Mr Adams is required to
refrain from fundraising, but Sinn Fein has set up an organisation in the US
and wants to start collecting from Irish Americans.
A senior US official said:
'Basically, I wouldn't rule it out. We've got some issues we're continuing
to work through with him.'
The US has said it can only allow fundraising if the IRA stops buying
weapons in the US, and if there is concrete progress towards disarming the
terrorist group. Sinn Fein is also trying to set up transparent accounting
procedures that would offer some assurance money it raised is not going to
the IRA.
</TEXT>
